node.text:
Sometimes, you find a film that speaks to you as an educator, a parent, and a human being. #ConfettiMovie is that film for me. Thanks to Dada Films for allowing me to watch @confettimovie before its release in theaters this Friday, August 20th. Swipe for the trailer.

Synopsis: Meimei is considered an outcast in her school in China after learning she has dyslexia (as do 1 in 10 people worldwide). Meimei and her mother embark on an international journey from China to New York, where Meimei’s mother will stop at nothing to ensure her daughter receives everything she needs and is seen as the amazing child she really is.

The Adventure Challenge book has fifty unique ideas to spark fun with the entire family- one for almost every weekend of the year! So we will never run out of ideas to make the most of our time together. Want to get in on your own adventure? Click the link in my bio and use code SAVE20 for a discount. Can't wait to have more adventures!

node.text:
We can’t “take it off.” If a student honestly doesn’t need an accommodation anymore, that’s wonderful! After all, that’s the GOAL! But it’s not something that can just be done. It needs data to support it from progress monitoring. It needs a full IEP meeting with the whole team (teachers, service providers, parent, and student) being in agreement. Remember, an IEP is a legal document that must be followed as it’s written. It can be amended and updated, but not on a whim.
.
.
.

Progress monitoring is essential when it comes to tracking student progress to determine if interventions and accommodations are working or need to be revised. I usually do progress monitoring for academics once a week, and i track the scores/reports in my digital sped binder. Here, I’m covering my two biggest tips for progress monitoring in the classroom. Drop your questions in the comments, and let’s keep the conversation going!
.

Want to see a picture of my classroom? Here you go. Due to sharing a room and scheduling, I will be mobile! It’s not ideal, and I’m really heartbroken over having set up an entire classroom and then not getting to use it. But I’m making the most of it. My ELA visuals will go to the ELA classroom. My math visuals will go to the math interventionist’s room (where I’ll be parking my cart one class period a day). It wasn’t the most fun news to find out the night before school started, but I’ve had a chance to let it sink in, and I think a cart of supplies is going to be my best option. If I’ve learned anything, it’s that being flexible is key. So tomorrow, I’ll load this bad boy up and get to work! Wish me luck (and send me all the coffee)
.
.

As you begin the new school year, make sure you build those relationships from the start!

First #feetupfriday of the new school year. I started my new digital sped binder for my new caseload. I read the IEPs I currently have access to. I was trained on two new instructional programs. I hung decorations. And now, it’s time to mentally prepare. One more work day Monday and then kids come back and it’s time to dive into learning! It was the shortest summer ever (literally- only 8 weeks), but I’m excited to meet my new favorite students and see some old favorites, too. How much do you have left of your summer?

node.text:
Four years ago, I left my comfort zone. I left everything I had ever done in order to step into a new role. I gave up my previous tenured position to pursue my dream of being a special education teacher. And today, I earned that tenure back while living out my passion for sped in the role of a lifetime. The last three years have brought wisdom and humility and praise and tears. They have brought me some of the most incredible opportunities, amazing friends, and the best students. And to think I almost let all of this pass me by in favor of being “comfortable.” So please, take this as your sign that it’s never too late to go after your dreams, and then when you reach them, DREAM BIGGER!
.
.
.
